It is a little early.
But it still seems like a thing that is happening.

Reasons I'm skeptical are that every character that was leaked for the Dragons deck made sense. None of them were new characters either.

Even if it's true, I don't think it's necessarily a bad thing. These products are already going to be inherently limited by being tribal. I think it's a good idea to use multiple types as it adds variety. Taigam is a great example for that.

how do you guys deal with players that are making obviously bad choices? Sometimes to the extent that they just give the game to other players?
Depends on how well I know them

If it's a complete stranger imo you just gotta suck it up. Maybe if you're the best communicator in the world you can point it out in a productive way, but 99.9% of the time they're going to think you're some asshole

If it's someone I know I try to find time during the next game shuffle to point out something I could have done to keep Player X from winning, then maybe try to feather in the thing they did as well to kind of create a comiserating-over-our-mistakes vibe
We have a term for this in our playgroup: CATA - Completely Arbitrary Threat Assessment. You never want to go CATAtonic.

lol. Its probably the only thing that frustrates me in a game. I guess I just can't handle people who don't know how to play. Not that I dislike new players. I help them learn as much as possible; but for instance, there was a guy that had been playing for 6 years and would always destroy something random on the field instead of the 50/50 animar.
I'll gladly leave a 50/50 animar alive if it's going to attack my opponents and not me
threat assessment varies for each player
not just based on skill, but based on the game state

If it's someone that I'm good friends with, we tend to razz each other quite a bit so we'll call each other out. If it's someone I don't know or don't like playing against I tend to stoneface ask "why..."
Or roll out 30 sarcastic comments about me not being the person they need to worry about
I do think there is game state to take in. I think the example was not thebest. There were plenty of times that he could have destroyed a infinite combo before it happened, and decided not to.

We were playing with one kid that didn't pick up on social cues very often and it was frustrating the hell out of me, so I ended up talking to him like Will Ferrell on the Dissing Your Dog skit from SNL and he still never realized how befuddled we were with him
"Now, what we're going to do is ask ourselves 'will this kill me?' And the answer is yes, so you should worry about that and not my cluestone that does nothing...."

The one that really frustrates me is when it's not necessarily bad threat assessment but it fucks the game anyway. We had a Breya eggs player last week intentionally skip like 10 Rhystic Study triggers on his turn durdling around with zero drop artifacts he was recurring trying to hit some combo, but his combo got stopped and he got killed. Problem was he kinda fucked the rest of us letting the Rhystic guy draw that much. I cant' blame him since ignoring it to win makes sense but it sucks seeing  someone's suicide turn kinda guarentee one other person's win
Then there's the people just ignorant of the fact that Rhystic Study is strong so they don't pay, but that's a different thing
Always pay for Study. Always.

Well if the person with it is tapped out and you think you're gonna win you don't have to. I haven't paid in that situation. This was just an extreme version of that since he was dicking around with baubles and salvaging station and it wound up being a ton of spells. In his shoes with that deck I'd probably have done the same. Just sucks that if it fails it wrecks the game for everyone else.
Jeremy, I'm stealing CATA for our next episode
Feel free to use it!
